.SH REINSTALL

The
.B reinstall
command performs a complete operating system reinstallation.

.B WARNING:
This operation destroys all existing data.

Features include:

.IP \(bu 2
Network-based installation

.IP \(bu 2
Supports Linux and Windows targets

.IP \(bu 2
Independent of current system state

.IP \(bu 2
Suitable for recovery or reprovisioning

.SH BACKUP

The
.B backup
command creates incremental backups using:

.IP \(bu 2
rsync local snapshots

.IP \(bu 2
Remote rsync over SSH

.IP \(bu 2
Cloud storage via rclone

Backups are incremental and optimized for efficiency and fast restore.

.SH BOOT-RECOVERY

The
.B boot-recovery
command creates and restores boot-critical snapshots.

This includes:

.IP \(bu 2
Bootloader

.IP \(bu 2
Kernel

.IP \(bu 2
Initramfs

.IP \(bu 2
Root filesystem metadata

Useful for recovering from boot failures.

.SH REPAIR

The
.B repair
command restores network configuration from snapshots.

This allows recovery from:

.IP \(bu 2
Firewall misconfiguration

.IP \(bu 2
Interface errors

.IP \(bu 2
Routing failures

Especially useful for remote servers.

.SH MIGRATE

The
.B migrate
command transfers entire systems.

Supported methods:

.TP
.B dd
Block-level cloning.

.TP
.B rsync
File-level migration.

Used for:

.IP \(bu 2
Server replacement

.IP \(bu 2
Failover preparation

.IP \(bu 2
Infrastructure migration

.SH SYS-INFO

Displays live system statistics including:

.IP \(bu 2
CPU usage

.IP \(bu 2
Memory usage

.IP \(bu 2
Disk usage

.IP \(bu 2
Network statistics

.IP \(bu 2
Load average

Provides functionality similar to
.BR top (1)
and
.BR htop (1).

.SH CRON

Provides an interface for configuring scheduled automation tasks.

Supports:

.IP \(bu 2
